revision.text:
{{italic title}} '''''Alam al-Jabarut''''' ({{lang-ar|عالم الجبروت}}, meaning the world of power<ref>Cyril Glassé, Huston Smith ''The New Encyclopedia of Islam'' Rowman Altamira 2003 {{ISBN|978-0-759-10190-6}} page 145</ref>) is the highest realm in [[Islamic cosmology]]. The realm ''[[Malakut|Al-Malakut]]'' is below ''Alam al Jabarut'', but still higher than ''[[Alam al Mulk]]''. The higher realms impinge the realms below and are not separated worlds.<ref>Amira El-Zein ''Islam, Arabs, and Intelligent World of the Jinn'' Syracuse University Press 2009 {{ISBN|978-0-815-65070-6}} page 6</ref> Although some scholars were not able to see any difference between ''Alam al Jabarut'' and ''Al-Malakut'',<ref>N. Hanif ''Biographical Encyclopaedia of Sufis: Central Asia and Middle East'' Sarup & Sons 2002 {{ISBN|978-8-176-25266-9}} page 307</ref> others thought this to be the realm of [[Islamic view of angels|angels]] and [[Ruh|spirits]] and the other a realm below. Thus this realm is also considered to be the created aspect of ''[[Rasul]]'' and the created reality of [[Adam in Islam|Adam]], here representing the ''perfect human'' ([[Al-Insān al-Kāmil]]).
==Angelic realm== While angels also dwell in ''Al-Malakut'' to encounter humans and perform tasks on earth, the most elected angels inhabit ''Al-Jabarut''.<ref>N. Hanif ''Biographical Encyclopaedia of Sufis: Central Asia and Middle East'' Sarup & Sons 2002 {{ISBN|978-8-176-25266-9}} page 307</ref> Therefore, this is the domain of angelic manifestations and therefore the realm of ''archetypes'', ''thrones'' and ''powers'' and also the [[jannah|paradise]] of the [[afterlife]], with the exception of the ''supreme paradise''.<ref>Cyril Glassé, Huston Smith ''The New Encyclopedia of Islam'' Rowman Altamira 2003 {{ISBN|978-0-759-10190-6}} page 144</ref> This realm is thus eternal existence, while the others are created and limited.<ref>N. Hanif ''Biographical Encyclopaedia of Sufis: Central Asia and Middle East'' Sarup & Sons 2002 {{ISBN|978-8-176-25266-9}} page 306</ref>
== See also == *[[Beri'ah]] *[[Sufi cosmology]]
