{{Infobox waterfall | name = Ozone Falls | photo = Ozone-falls-tennessee1.jpg | photo_width = | photo_caption = Ozone Falls | location = [[Cumberland County, Tennessee]] | coords = {{Coord|35.88045|-84.81001|region:US_type:waterbody|display=inline,title}} | coords_ref = <ref name="tnlandforms">{{cite web |url=http://tnlandforms.us/landforms/m.php?wpt=CUF003 |title=Ozone Falls 110' |last=Dunigan |first=Tom |date= |publisher=Tennessee landforms |access-date=May 10, 2017 |quote=35.88045, -84.81001 }}</ref> | elevation = | type = Plunge | height = {{convert|110|ft|m}}<ref name="tnlandforms"/> | width = | height_longest = | average_width = | number_drops = | average_flow = | watercourse = Fall Creek | world_rank = }} '''Ozone Falls''' is a waterfall located in [[Cumberland County, Tennessee]] in the [[Ozone Falls State Natural Area]] and [[Justin P. Wilson Cumberland Trail State Park | Cumberland Trail State Park]]. Ozone Falls is situated along Fall Creek, which drains a short section of the [[Cumberland Plateau]] between the [[Crab Orchard Mountains]] to the west and [[Walden Ridge]] to the east. The creek flows down from its source high in the Crab Orchard Mountains for a mile or so before steadying briefly as it enters the community of [[Ozone, Tennessee|Ozone]]. Fall Creek enters the state natural area just after it passes under [[U.S. Route 70 in Tennessee|U.S. Route 70]], which runs perpendicular to it. The creek spills over Ozone Falls a few hundred meters south of US-70. The trailhead is located along US-70.<ref>{{cite book|last=Roark|first=Kelley|title=Hiking Tennessee|year=1996|publisher=Falcon|location=Helena, Mont.|isbn=978-1-56044-394-0|pages=158–161}}</ref>
{{Commons category|Ozone Falls, Tennessee}}
==References== {{Reflist}}
[[Category:Waterfalls of Tennessee]] [[Category:Landforms of Cumberland County, Tennessee]]
{{waterfall-stub}} {{CumberlandCountyTN-geo-stub}}

The '''Pacific Border province''' is a physiographic province of the [[Physiographic regions of the world]] physical geography system.
==Description== The Pacific Border province encompasses most of the [[North American]] [[West Coast of the United States|Pacific Coast]], with the southern end at the start of the Lower California-[[Peninsular Ranges]] Province in [[Southern California]]. The Pacific Border province is in the larger [[Pacific Mountain System]] Division—Region. The region is prone to earthquakes, residing along the eastern edge of the [[Pacific Ring of Fire]].
===Sections=== The Pacific Border province contains nine separate and smaller sections: *[[Puget Trough]] *[[Olympic Mountains]] *[[Oregon Coast Range]] *[[Klamath Mountains]] *[[Central Valley (California)|California Trough]] *[[California Coast Ranges]] *[[Transverse Ranges]]
==References== {{refimprove|date=May 2011}} {{reflist}} {{-}}
{{Geography topics}} {{Physical geography topics}}
{{coord |42|N|124|W|type:adm1st_region:US_scale:5000000|display=title}}
[[Category:Physiographic provinces]] [[Category:Geography of North America]] [[Category:Geography of the United States]] [[Category:Regions of the Western United States]] [[Category:Pacific Coast Ranges]]
{{US-geo-stub}}

The '''Pernambuco fault''' or '''Pernambuco Shear Zone''' in northeastern [[Brazil]] is a [[Fault (geology)|fault]] radiating from the [[Trans Brazilian Lineament]] eastwards to the coast, a major geological feature.<ref name=Fairhead2007/>
The Pernambuco-Alagoas domain, part of the [[Borborema Province]], is primarily made of rocks aged between 1,600 and 1,000 million years, significantly younger than the areas to the north and south.<ref name=Pankhurst2008/>
The Pernambuco fault in this domain is a continuation of the [[Foumban Shear Zone]] in [[Cameroon]], itself the western end of the [[Central African Shear Zone]].<ref name=Fairhead2007/> To the west, the fault splays into numerous faults along a distance of about 50&nbsp;km, suggesting that the crust was weak at this point, which is on the line where [[South America]] separated from [[Africa]] around 115 million years ago.<ref name=Vauchez1992/>
==References== {{reflist|1|refs= <ref name=Fairhead2007>{{cite journal |url = http://pubs.getech.com/publications/The%20Role%20of%20Gravity%20and%20Aeromagnetic%20Data%20in%20Mapping%20Mega%20Gondwana%20Crustal%20Lineaments%20the%20Argentina%20Brazil%20%20Algeria%20(ABA)%20Lineament.pdf |title = The Role of Gravity and Aeromagnetic Data in Mapping Mega Gondwana Crustal Lineaments: the Argentina - Brazil – Algeria (ABA) Lineament |author = J D Fairhead, Nasreddine Bournas and M Chaker Raddadi |journal = SEG |year = 2007 |accessdate = 2011-01-30 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110711090717/http://pubs.getech.com/publications/The%20Role%20of%20Gravity%20and%20Aeromagnetic%20Data%20in%20Mapping%20Mega%20Gondwana%20Crustal%20Lineaments%20the%20Argentina%20Brazil%20%20Algeria%20%28ABA%29%20Lineament.pdf |archivedate = 2011-07-11 |df = }}</ref> <ref name=Pankhurst2008>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dIEzMrq0iyMC&pg=PA91 |page=91 |title=West Gondwana: pre-Cenozoic correlations across the South Atlantic Region |author=Robert J. Pankhurst |publisher=Geological Society |year=2008 |ISBN=1-86239-247-1}}</ref> <ref name=Vauchez1992>{{cite journal |url=http://geology.geoscienceworld.org/cgi/content/abstract/20/11/1007 |title=Termination of a continental-scale strike-slip fault in partially melted crust: The West Pernambuco shear zone, northeast Brazil |author=Alain Vauchez and Marcos Egydio da Silva |journal=Geology |date=November 1992 |volume=20| issue = 11 |pages=1007–1010 |doi=10.1130/0091-7613(1992)020<1007:TOACSS>2.3.CO;2 |accessdate=2011-02-03}}</ref> }}
{{coord|7|50|S|38|15|W|type:landmark_region:BR_dim:300000|display=title}} {{Major South American geological formations}}
[[Category:Seismic faults of Brazil]] [[Category:Geology of Brazil]]
{{palaeo-geo-stub}}

